on><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC7442720</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">32398324</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Olaparib plus durvalumab, with or without bevacizumab, as treatment in PARP inhibitor-na&#xef;ve platinum-sensitive relapsed ovarian cancer: a phase II multi-cohort study. Drew Y, Kim JW, Penson RT, et al. Clin Cancer Res. 2024;30:50&#x2013;62.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC10767301</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">37939124</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Evaluation of treatment with talazoparib and avelumab in patients with recurrent mismatch repair proficient endometrial cancer. Konstantinopoulos PA, Gockley AA, Xiong N, et al. JAMA Oncol. 2022;8:1317&#x2013;1322.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC9335244</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35900726</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Efficacy and safety of durvalumab with olaparib in metastatic or recurrent endometrial cancer (phase II DOMEC trial) Post CC, Westermann AM, Boere IA, et al. Gynecol Oncol. 2022;165:223&#x2013;229.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">35287967</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Bevacizumab, olaparib, and durvalumab in patients with relapsed ovarian cancer: a phase II clinical trial from the GINECO group. Freyer G, Floquet A, Tredan O, et al. Nat Commun. 2024;15</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC10914754</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">38443333</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Triplet maintenance therapy of olaparib, pembrolizumab and bevacizumab in women with BRCA wild-type, platinum-sensitive recurrent ovarian cancer: the multicenter, single-arm phase II study OPEB-01/APGOT-OV4. Kim YN, Park B, Kim JW, et al. Nat Commun. 2023;14</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC10482952</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">37673858</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Niraparib, dostarlimab, and bevacizumab as combination therapy in pretreated, advanced platinum-resistant ovarian cancer: findings from cohort A of the OPAL phase II trial. Liu JF, Gaillard S, Hendrickson AE, et al. JCO Precis Oncol. 2024;8</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC11371093</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">38754056</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Programmed cell death 1 (PD-1) and its ligand (PD-L1) in common cancers and their correlation with molecular cancer type. Gatalica Z, Snyder C, Maney T, et al. Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev. 2014;23:2965&#x2013;2970.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">25392179</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Durvalumab plus carboplatin/paclitaxel followed by maintenance durvalumab with or without olaparib as first-line treatment for advanced endometrial cancer: the phase III DUO-E trial. Westin SN, Moore K, Chon HS, et al. J Clin Oncol. 2024;42:283&#x2013;299.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC10824389</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">37864337</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Dostarlimab and niraparib in primary advanced ovarian cancer. Hardy-Bessard AC, Pujade-Lauraine E, Moore RG, et al. Ann Oncol. 2025;36:1503&#x2013;1513.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">40461381</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41228382</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>13</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>16</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">2072-6694</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>17</Volume><Issue>21</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Nov</Month><Day>06</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Cancers</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Cancers (Basel)</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>The Real-World Impact of PARP Inhibitor Maintenance Therapy in High Grade Serous Tubo-Ovarian and Peritoneal Cancers.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">3591</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3390/cancers17213591</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Pivotal clinical trials have led to the routine clinical use of PARP inhibitor (PARPi) (olaparib, niraparib, or rucaparib) maintenance therapy in high-grade serous tubo-ovarian and peritoneal cancers. Whether various PARPis have comparable clinical impact in the real-world is an area of ongoing investigation.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">We conducted a retrospective study of all patients who received PARPi maintenance therapy at Nottingham Cancer Centre from October 2017 to April 2025. Clinical data were extracted from multidisciplinary team electronic health records, including age, BRCA mutation status, HRD status, treatment history, type of PARP inhibitor received, progression-free survival (PFS), and overall survival (OS).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">A total of 177 patients had received PARPi therapy with a mean age of 63 years at diagnosis. In all, 94/177 (53.1%) had received PARPi as primary maintenance, while 83/177 (46.9%) were treated in the recurrent setting. All together, 25/177 (14.1%) had BRCA1 germline mutation and 21/177 (11.9%) had BRCA2 germline mutation. In the primary olaparib setting, PFS was significantly better in BRCA2 germline-mutated patients compared to BRCA1 germline-mutated patients [median PFS was not reached vs. 29.0 months, respectively, <i>p</i> = 0.002]. In BRCA, wild-type patients receiving primary niraparib, median PFS was 11 months. Median PFS for patients with upfront surgery was 37 months compared to 19 months in the interval debulking group but not significant (<i>p</i> = 0.49). In the recurrent setting, there was no significant difference in median PFS between niraparib and rucaparib [10 months vs. 9 months, <i>p</i> = 0.594].</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">BRCA2 germline-mutated patients obtained significantly greater benefit from olaparib compared to BRCA1-mutated patients. PFS benefit from niraparib (primary or recurrent setting) is comparable to clinical trials. There was no difference in benefit between niraparib and rucaparib in the recurrent setting.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Al-Ani</LastName><ForeName>Maryam</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, Nottingham University Hospitals, Hucknall Road, Nottingham NG5 1PB, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Baraka</LastName><ForeName>Bahaaeldin</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, Nottingham University Hospitals, Hucknall Road, Nottingham NG5 1PB, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Mathiyalagan</LastName><ForeName>Navin</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, Nottingham University Hospitals, Hucknall Road, Nottingham NG5 1PB, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sarwar</LastName><ForeName>Muhammad Adeel</ForeName><Initials>MA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, Nottingham University Hospitals, Hucknall Road, Nottingham NG5 1PB, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Segaran</LastName><ForeName>Avinash</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Oncology, Nottingham University Hospitals, Hucknall Road, Nottingham NG5 1PB, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><La